You can `filter` the `Object.values` array based on whether a value is an array (using [`Array.isArray()`][1]) and checking its `length`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var arr = {
      key1: &#39;progress&#39;,
      key2: &#39;done&#39;,
      key3: [&#39;new&#39;, &#39;12&#39;],
      key4: [&#39;checking&#39;, &#39;10&#39;]
    };

    var result = Object.values(arr).filter(v =&gt; Array.isArray(v) &amp;&amp; v.length &gt; 1);
    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/isArray

To elaborate on the previous answer, if you want to exactly get `{key3:[&#39;new&#39;,&#39;12&#39;],key4:[&#39;checking&#39;,&#39;10&#39;]}` as result value, you need to then use the array values you found to build a new object.

It can be done like this, by looping on the `keys` of the original `arr`, checking each value against the `arrayValues` you found, and creating a new key-value pair in the `result` object when a match is found

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var arr = {
      key1: &#39;progress&#39;,
      key2: &#39;done&#39;,
      key3: [&#39;new&#39;, &#39;12&#39;],
      key4: [&#39;checking&#39;, &#39;10&#39;]
    };

    var arrayValues = Object.values(arr).filter(v =&gt; Array.isArray(v) &amp;&amp; v.length &gt; 1);

    let result = {}
    Object.keys(arr).forEach(key =&gt; arrayValues.includes(arr[key]) ? result[key] = arr[key] : null)

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

There are many more elegant ways of doing this, though.

